<br>
I don’t believe that it is. Although a solar sail is a heat engine insofar as the source of the energy is a big hot thermonuclear fusion reactor (well, actually it isn't. I think a “relatively cool, quantum tunnelling, fusion reactor” would be a more accurate description! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) What actually happens as the photons strike the sail is not actually a heat engine process.<br>
<br>
A heat engine works by allowing heat energy to flow from a high temperature source to a low temperature sink in a controlled manner in order to extract useful mechanical work.<br>
<br>
Put a different way a Carnot heat engine is a way of converting some of the randomised thermal kinetic energy from a high temperature heat source into somewhat more useful directional mechanical kinetic energy.<br>
<br>
The Carnot equations tell us what level of *tax* we have to pay to achieve this de-randomisation. (They also tell us that we can run the whole thing backwards and get our money back.)<br>
<br>
However this *tax* does not apply when we are converting one kind of directional energy into another. Though there are always engineering losses, the efficiency with which the directional kinetic energy of the wind or a river is converted into the rotational kinetic energy of a windmill or a waterwheel is not determined by Carnot cycle rules.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that the same applies with solar sails.<br>
<br>
A solar sail converts the directional kinetic energy of the photons into directional kinetic energy of the spacecraft. (And vice versa IE Braking)<br>
<br>
The energy transfer mechanisms is red shift when the ship is moving away from the light source and blue shift when it is moving towards it (Braking)<br>
<br>
Of course an interesting aside this means that a perfect mirror doesn’t only have to be 100% reflective, it also needs to have infinite mass.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
